The absence of extant species from climatically suitable areas may result from time-lagged migration or the exclusion of species from established colonization (
 Normand et al., 2011). The migration performance of a species is related to its intrinsic dispersal ability and extrinsic influencing factors, such as the locations of ice age refugia, geographical barriers, habitat fragmentation and competition with established vegetation (
 Davis, 1986; 
 Prentice, Bartlein & Webb, 1991; 
 Svenning & Skov, 2004). The factors that drive a species out of an established colonization area include the local edaphic conditions, biotic interactions and human deforestation. The factors contributing to the absence of 
 P. amabilis from climatically suitable areas depend on the specific geographic position.
